{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"04c84b7c-bf33-4b6f-80ce-b17b5f30c4a1","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and hook into the window events:\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, and `OnResumed()`.\n\n**Key mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` / `Backgrounding` |\n| `OnResume` | `Resumed` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac-specific and lets you save state. `Stopped` fires on all platforms. For platform-specific hooks, see `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f77738d1-658c-40cf-af72-be9a50ba20e6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated()`\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Backgrounding` event or override `Window.OnBackgrounding()`\n\n\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` event or override `Window.OnResumed()`\n\nYou can also use the `ILifecycleEvents` interface for platform-specific lifecycle events. The `Application` class in .NET MAUI doesn't have those same lifecycle methods—the recommended approach is working with the `Window` lifecycle instead.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Window` class provides the lifecycle events you need: `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding`, each with corresponding override methods. For `OnStart`, I'd override `CreateWindow()` in the `App` class or create a custom `Window` subclass and override `OnCreated()`. For `OnSleep`, that maps to `Window.Backgrounding`.","outputTokens":910,"requestId":"7FC5:229004:6216D76:6AE6515:69F1573D"},"id":"9699beaf-50c6-4446-bf6b-3697c362f8f3","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:56:45.886Z","parentId":"67fada08-c47b-4956-91f5-c76f3debc1a4"}
